<h3><b>Copyright / Legality / Misindexed Media</b></h3>
<p>
<a name="c1"><b>Q: I’m an artist, photographer, or company who sees some of my copyrighted material being shared illegally. What can I do to stop it?</b></a><br>
A: See our <a href="../../copyright/default.asp">copyright</a> section for steps you can take to protect your work.<br><br>

We are in the process of automating our filtering system. This will allow copyright holders to submit their pictures to a secure web site. These pictures are then added to our filtering list and deleted.<br><br>

<a name="c2"><b>Q: My search returned some media that is obviously illegal. Are these files now saved to my system? What can I do to help stop these files from being distributed?</b></a><br>
A: In order to save a file, you must first add it to your download queue and then click ‘save’ in the completed downloads section. If you did not do both of these steps, the image has not been saved to your computer.<br><br>

We are in the process of upgrading the AMS client to provide suspicious file tracking. In the future, you will be able to mark a file as suspicious. These files will be reviewed by our staff and removed if necessary.<br><br>

<a name="c3"><b>Q: I downloaded some files that obviously don’t match what I searched for. How can I prevent this?</b></a><br>
A: We rely on end users to index media correctly. Unfortunately, we have no control over how our users index each piece of media.<br><br>

We are currently working hard to correct this problem. We spot check newly indexed media to find accounts that habitually misindex files. When found, we put these accounts in “untrusted” mode and any future indexing from them is ignored by our system. We are also working on upgrading the AMS client to include client side marking of misindexed files. Any files you find misindexed, you can report with a simple click of the mouse. Our staff will review the media and remove/reindex it if necessary.<br><br>

<a name="c4"><b>Q: What is to stop me from incorrectly indexing files just to screw up other people.</b></a><br>
A: Absolutely nothing. We are reliant on end users to correctly index files. If enough people flag a file as incorrectly indexed, we will take steps to remove it from our database, or revoke user accounts as needed.<br><br>
</p>


